    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5931;-8752,1280;Inherit;False;446.4383;187.0728;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Cook-Torrance GSF was created to solve three cases of Geometric attenuation.$$The
    first case states that the light is reflected without interference, the second
    case states that some reflected light is blocked after reflection, and the third
    case states that some light is blocked before reaching the next microfacet;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5932;-9152,1392;Inherit;False;161;100;Vectorized;;0,0,0,1;for
    Optimiziation & Streamlining;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5933;-9056,1968;Inherit;False;350.6726;114.2719;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Duer GSF produces similar results as the Ashikhmin-Shirley, but is more suited
    towards Isotropic BRDFs, or very slightly Anisotropic BRDF ;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5934;-8896,1696;Inherit;False;189.5706;115.9266;;;0,0,0,1;Hard
    coding Power with multiple can be a lot cheaper than use of power node;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5935;-8096,2320;Inherit;False;197.4839;131.3042;;;0,0,0,1;This
    is a refactor of the Walter et al. GSF algorithm by multiplying the GSF by NdotV/NdotV.;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5936;-8976,2448;Inherit;False;192.4;100;Vectorized;;0,0,0,0.5019608;to
    simplify and Optimize the Algorithm;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5937;-8976,2576;Inherit;False;168.6667;103.2001;Add
    0.1;;0,0,0,0.5019608;To Prevent NaN in Division and Output;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5938;-9152,2912;Inherit;False;284.6823;162.4425;;;0,0,0,1;By
    multiplying the dot product of the normal and light by the dot product of the
    normal and our viewpoint we get an accurate portrayal of how light affects the
    surface of an object based on our view;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5939;-8944,3936;Inherit;False;290.8142;126.5519;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Kelemen GSF presents an appropriately energy conserving GSF. This is an extreme
    Approximation of the Cook-Torrance GSF;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5940;-8592,3360;Inherit;False;251.7352;158.2921;;;0,0,0,1;This
    is a modified form of the Kelemen Approximation of Cook-Torrance$$It has been
    modified to produce the Keleman GSF distributed by roughness;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5941;-10464,3712;Inherit;False;202.4833;181.3258;PI
    Inv Approx;;0,0,0,1;Near:$0.797884560802865$$Exact:$sqrt(2 / Pi)$$PI Inv Approx$0.7978846$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5943;-8576,4416;Inherit;False;249.2864;140.2768;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Kurt GSF model is proposed to help control the Distribution of Anisotropic surfaces
    based on the surface roughness$$$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5944;-8976,4960;Inherit;False;299.9617;157.5574;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Neumann-Neumann GSF is another example of a GSF suited for Anisotropic Normal
    Distribution. It produces more pronounced geometric shading based on the greater
    of view direction or light direction;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5945;-8560,5376;Inherit;False;318.6954;162.5898;;;0,0,0,1;Schlick
    has made several approximations of the Smith GSF that can be applied to other
    Smith GSFs as well$$Schlick Approx: The different Approximations of other GSFs
    by Schlick$$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5946;-9168,5376;Inherit;False;155.03;100;Vectorized;;0,0,0,0.5019608;to
    simplify and Optimize the Algorithm;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5947;-8800,5696;Inherit;False;637.9452;190.5282;Schlick's
    Approximations;;0,0,0,0.5019608;Most of Schlick's Approx.-s mostly modify the
    'Roughness' value and the rest of the Algorithim stays the same$$Base: \"the
    baseline Schlick Approximation of Smith GSF\" $$Beckman: \"It works by multiplying
    roughness by the square root of 2/PI.\" $$GGX: \"The Schlick Approximation of
    GGX simply divides our roughness value by two.\"  ;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5948;-8720,5568;Inherit;False;184;100;Max
    0.1;;0,0,0,0.5019608;To Prevent NaN in Division and Output;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5955;-7472,6320;Inherit;False;258.4333;125.8819;;;0,0,0,1;Originally
    created to be used with the Beckman NDF, Walter et al. surmised that it is an
    appropriate GSF for use with the Phong NDF$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5956;-9152,6320;Inherit;False;200.333;101.4815;Vectorized;;0,0,0,0.5019608;to
    simplify and Optimize the Algorithm;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5957;-8528,6048;Inherit;False;177;100;Max
    Non Zero;;0,0,0,0.5019608;To prevent Nan in the Division and Output;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5958;-7728,7168;Inherit;False;193.5849;104.6059;;;0,0,0,1;Unity's
    Version of the Smith GGX GSF method;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5959;-9136,7040;Inherit;False;128.3999;109.5996;Vectorized;;0,0,0,0.5019608;to
    simplify and Optimize the Algorithm;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5960;-8624,7648;Inherit;False;762.2997;191.3541;;;0,0,0,0.5019608;The
    common form of the GGX GSF, Walter et al. created this function to be used with
    any NDF. $$Walter et al. felt that the GSF \"has relatively little effect on
    the shape of the BSDF [Bi-Directional Scattering Distribution Function], except
    near grazing angles or for very rough surfaces, but is needed to maintain energy
    conservation.$$With this in mind, they created a GSF that respected this principle,
    using Roughness as a driving force for the GSF$$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5961;-7808,7552;Inherit;False;230.4163;112.9266;;;0,0,0,1;The
    common form of the GGX GSF, Walter et al. created this function to be used with
    any NDF $;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5962;-9152,7584;Inherit;False;155.5999;100;Vectorized;;0,0,0,0.5019608;to
    simplify and Optimize the Algorithm;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;5963;-9136,8128;Inherit;False;305.0074;115.1098;;;0.06603771,0.06603771,0.06603771,1;The
    Ward GSF is a strengthened Implicit GSF. Ward uses this approach to strengthen
    the Normal Distribution Functions $;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6446;-7328,9216;Inherit;False;290.4297;157.1641;Anisotropic;;0,0,0,1;Use
    the float to set the direction of the anisotropy effect. Negative values make
    the effect vertical, and positive values make the effect horizontal.  This stretches
    the anisotropic highlights in the given direction.;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6447;-7856,8704;Inherit;False;416.2261;226.2658;List
    of Dot Products Used for NDFs;;0,0,0,0.5019608;in order as they appear in the
    inputs of the NDFs.$$-NdotH for All but Bling-Phong$$-RdotV for Bling-Phong$$-HdotX
    & HdotY for Both TrowBridge Reitz & Ward Anisotropic$$-NdotL & NdotV for Ward
    Anisotropic$$read \"Dot Products List\" notes for details per Dot Product;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6448;-6624,9136;Inherit;False;281.9233;136.0679;Aniso
    Vector;;0,0,0,1;Vectorized & Precomputed in the Core to save on both Compile
    time & Performance for Anisotropic NDFs, since they both use same math anyways.;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6449;-9456,8592;Inherit;False;238.7957;133.7377;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Beckman Normal Distribution function Accounts for the roughness, as well as the
    dot product between our normal and half direction $$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6450;-10144,8800;Inherit;False;223;100;Max
    .0001;;0,0,0,0.5019608;prevents the Specular dot from \"disappearing\" at 'Low/Zero
    Roughness\";0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6452;-8784,9568;Inherit;False;389.0801;166.0377;Blinn-Phong;;0,0,0,0.5019608;Blinn
    approximation of Phong specularity was created as an optimization of the Phong
    Specular Model. Blinn decided that it was faster to produce the dot product of
    the normal and half vector, than it was to calculate the reflect vector of light
    every frame. The algorithms do produce much different results, with Blinn being
    softer than Phong $$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6454;-9728,10000;Inherit;False;293.8874;150.797;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Gaussian Normal Distribution model is not as popular as some of the other models,
    as it tends to produce much softer specular highlights than can be desired at
    higher smoothness values $;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6455;-10096,10096;Inherit;False;207.7999;100;Max
    .0001;;0,0,0,0.5019608;prevents the Specular dot from \"disappearing\" at 'Low/Zero
    Roughness\";0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6456;-9072,10448;Inherit;False;254.0076;144.8768;;;0,0,0,1;The
    specular highlight of the GGX Algorithm is very tight and hot, while still maintaining
    a smooth distribution across the surface;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6457;-10416,10368;Inherit;False;194;100;NdotH;;0.02830189,0.01268245,0.01268245,1;Light
    Wrapping set to custom .0001;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6458;-10272,10736;Inherit;False;165.2339;100;Roughness;;0,0,0,1;The
    surface Roughness value.;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6459;-9840,10736;Inherit;False;223;100;Max
    .0001;;0,0,0,0.5019608;prevents the Specular dot from \"disappearing\" at 'Low/Zero
    Roughness\";0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6460;-9216,11648;Inherit;False;334.9012;116.5612;;;0,0,0,1;The
    Trowbridge-Reitz approach was developed in the same paper as GGX, and produces
    remarkably similar results to the GGX algorithm$$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode,
    AmplifyShaderEditor, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6461;-9216,11792;Inherit;False;338.3152;130.4518;Difference
    to GGX;;0,0,0,1;The main noticeable difference is that the extreme edge of the
    object features a smoother highlight than the GGX, which is a more harsh falloff
    at the grazing angle$$;0;0\nNode;AmplifyShaderEditor.StickyNoteNode, AmplifyShaderEditor,
    Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null;6462;-10992,8784;Inherit;False;256.2408;137.3369;Roughness;;0,0,0,1;Low
    Roughness:$Should be Noted that low enough Roughness will lead the Specular Point
